ightmargin=0.5cm,\n  framexleftmargin=3mm,\n  framexrightmargin=3mm,\n  framesep=2mm,\n  rulecolor=\\color{subheadingcolor}\n}\n\n% Tables with text wrapping and proper column widths\n\\usepackage{booktabs}\n\\usepackage{longtable}\n\\usepackage{array}\n\\usepackage{tabularx}\n\\usepackage{calc}\n\n% Increase row height for readability\n\\renewcommand{\\arraystretch}{1.4}\n\n% Allow text wrapping in table cells by default\n\\newcolumntype{L}[1]{>{\\raggedright\\arraybackslash}p{#1}}\n\\newcolumntype{C}[1]{>{\\centering\\arraybackslash}p{#1}}\n\\newcolumntype{R}[1]{>{\\raggedleft\\arraybackslash}p{#1}}\n\n% Force Pandoc longtables to use full width and wrap text\n\\usepackage{etoolbox}\n\\AtBeginEnvironment{longtable}{\\footnotesize}\n\\makeatletter\n\\let\\oldlt\\longtable\n\\let\\endoldlt\\endlongtable\n\\def\\longtable{\\@ifnextchar[\\longtable@i \\longtable@ii}\n\\def\\longtable@i[#1]{\\begin{oldlt}[#1]}\n\\def\\longtable@ii{\\begin{oldlt}[c]}\n\\def\\endlongtable{\\end{oldlt}}\n\\makeatother\n\n% Prevent table columns from overflowing page margins\n\\setlength{\\tabcolsep}{4pt}\n\n% Links\n\\usepackage{hyperref}\n\\hypersetup{\n  colorlinks=true,\n  linkcolor=headingcolor,\n  urlcolor=linkblue,\n  pdfborder={0 0 0}\n}\n\n% Page header/footer\n\\usepackage{fancyhdr}\n\\pagestyle{fancy}\n\\fancyhf{}\n\\renewcommand{\\headrulewidth}{0.5pt}\n\\renewcommand{\\footrulewidth}{0.5pt}\n\\fancyhead[L]{\\leftmark}\n\\fancyhead[R]{\\thepage}\n\\fancyfoot[C]{\\small \\textbf{AI-generated} Study Material | \\textbf{Ram Kumar}, saas.expert.ram@gmail.com}\n\n% Better handling of images\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\setkeys{Gin}{width=0.8\\textwidth}\n\n% Line spacing\n\\usepackage{setspace}\n\\setstretch{1.15}\n\\usepackage{bookmark}\n\\IfFileExists{xurl.sty}{\\usepackage{xurl}}{} % add URL line breaks if available\n\\urlstyle{same}\n\\hypersetup{\n  hidelinks,\n  pdfcreator={LaTeX via pandoc}}\n\n\\author{}\n\\date{}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\n{\n\\setcounter{tocdepth}{3}\n\\tableofcontents\n}\n\\section{Data Classification and Machine\nLearning}\\label{data-classification-and-machine-learning}\n\n\\subsection{1. Learning Objectives}\\label{learning-objectives}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  Understand the fundamental concepts of supervised and unsupervised\n  learning.\n\\item\n  Define and differentiate between regression and classification\n  problems.\n\\item\n  Describe the key components of a linear regression model.\n\\item\n  Explain how to apply k-means clustering to group data.\n\\item\n  Understand the principles behind logistic regression and its use in\n  binary classification.\n\\item\n  Explain the concepts of bias, variance, and the bias-variance tradeoff\n  in machine learning.\n\\item\n  Describe how to use K-folds Cross Validation to measure model\n  performance.\n\\item\n  Understand the use of Support Vector Machines (SVMs) in classification\n  tasks.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{2. Executive Overview}\\label{executive-overview}\n\nData classification and machine learning are essential tools for\nextracting insights and making predictions from data. The field\nencompasses a vast range of techniques, from simple linear regression to\ncomplex neural networks. These methods are applied across numerous\nindustries, including finance, healthcare, marketing, and manufacturing,\nenabling businesses to automate processes, personalize customer\nexperiences, and gain a competitive advantage. The core challenge lies\nin selecting the appropriate algorithm and parameters for a given\nproblem, considering factors such as data volume, dimensionality, and\nthe desired level of accuracy. Effective utilization of these\ntechnologies requires a solid understanding of underlying mathematical\nand statistical principles, as well as familiarity with various software\ntools and libraries.\n\n\\subsection{3. Core Concepts \\& Technical\nDefinitions}\\label{core-concepts-technical-definitions}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Machine Learning:} A field of computer science that enables\n  systems to learn from data without being explicitly programmed. It\n  involves algorithms that identify patterns, make predictions, and\n  improve their performance over time through experience.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Supervised Learning:} A type of machine learning where the\n  algorithm learns from labeled data, meaning that each data point is\n  associated with a known output or target variable. The goal is to\n  learn a function that maps input features to this output.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Unsupervised Learning:} A type of machine learning where the\n  algorithm learns from unlabeled data, meaning that no output or target\n  variable is provided. The goal is to discover hidden patterns,\n  structures, or relationships within the data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Regression:} A supervised learning task where the algorithm\n  learns to predict a continuous numerical value. Examples include\n  predicting house prices or stock values.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Classification:} A supervised learning task where the\n  algorithm learns to assign data points to predefined categories or\n  classes. Examples include spam detection or image recognition.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Linear Regression:} A statistical method for modeling the\n  relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent\n  variables, assuming a linear relationship. It seeks to find the\n  best-fitting line that minimizes the sum of the squared differences\n  between observed and predicted values.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Logistic Regression:} A statistical method for predicting the\n  probability of a binary outcome (e.g., 0 or 1, yes or no) based on one\n  or more independent variables. It uses the sigmoid function to map the\n  linear combination of variables to a probability between 0 and 1.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{K-means Clustering:} An unsupervised learning algorithm that\n  partitions a dataset into \\emph{k} distinct clusters, where each data\n  point belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean (centroid).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Principal Component Analysis (PCA):} A dimensionality\n  reduction technique that transforms a dataset into a new coordinate\n  system where the principal components (eigenvectors) capture the\n  maximum variance in the data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Support Vector Machine (SVM):} A supervised learning algorithm\n  that finds an optimal hyperplane to separate data points belonging to\n  different classes, maximizing the margin between the hyperplane and\n  the closest data points.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Bias:} A systematic error in a model that arises from\n  simplifying assumptions or underfitting the data. High bias models\n  make strong assumptions about the data and tend to consistently miss\n  the true relationship.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Variance:} A measure of the sensitivity of a model to changes\n  in the training data. High variance models are overly complex and fit\n  the training data too closely, leading to poor generalization\n  performance on unseen data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Bias-Variance Tradeoff:} The fundamental challenge in machine\n  learning is to find a balance between bias and variance. Reducing bias\n  often increases variance, and vice versa. The goal is to find a model\n  that minimizes both bias and variance to achieve optimal performance.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{4. In-Depth Subject Matter\nCoverage}\\label{in-depth-subject-matter-coverage}\n\n\\subsubsection{1. Understanding Supervised\nLearning}\\label{understanding-supervised-learning}\n\nSupervised learning algorithms learn from labeled data, meaning that\neach data point is associated with a known output or target variable.\nThis approach is effective when you have a dataset where you know the\n“right” answers and you want to build a model that can predict those\nanswers for new, unseen data. The core process involves training the\nalgorithm on the labeled data, allowing it to learn the underlying\nrelationship between the input features and the output variable. The\naccuracy of the model depends heavily on the quality and quantity of the\ntraining data.\n\n\\textbf{Step-by-Step Process:}\n\n\\begin{enumerate}\n\\def\\labelenumi{\\arabic{enumi}.}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Data Preparation:} Clean and preprocess the data, handling\n  missing values, outliers, and data type conversions.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Feature Selection:} Select the most relevant features that\n  contribute to the prediction task.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Model Selection:} Choose an appropriate supervised learning\n  algorithm based on the nature of the data and the prediction task.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Model Training:} Train the algorithm using the labeled\n  training data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Model Evaluation:} Assess the model’s performance using\n  metrics like accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score on a separate\n  test dataset.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Model Tuning:} Adjust the model’s parameters to optimize its\n  performance.\n\\end{enumerate}\n\n\\textbf{Best Practices:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Data Quality is Paramount:} Ensure your training data is\n  accurate, complete, and representative of the real-world data you’ll\n  encounter.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Cross-Validation:} Use cross-validation techniques to get a\n  robust estimate of the model’s performance and prevent overfitting.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Feature Engineering:} Create new features from existing ones\n  to improve model accuracy.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Common Pitfalls:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Overfitting:} The model learns the training data too well and\n  fails to generalize to new data. Use techniques like regularization or\n  cross-validation to mitigate this.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Underfitting:} The model is too simple to capture the\n  underlying patterns in the data. Try using a more complex model or\n  adding more features.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Data Leakage:} Information from the test data is inadvertently\n  used during training. Properly separate your training and test\n  datasets.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{2. Understanding Linear\nRegression}\\label{understanding-linear-regression}\n\nLinear regression aims to establish a linear relationship between a\ndependent variable (the one we’re trying to predict) and one or more\nindependent variables (the predictors). The goal is to find the best-fit\nline that minimizes the sum of the squared differences between the\nactual values and the predicted values.\n\n\\textbf{Formula:} \\texttt{y\\ =\\ β₀\\ +\\ β₁x₁\\ +\\ β₂x₂\\ +\\ ...\\ +\\ βₘxₘ}\n\nWhere:\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\texttt{y} is the dependent variable.\n\\item\n  \\texttt{β₀} is the y-intercept (the value of y when all x’s are zero).\n\\item\n  \\texttt{β₁,\\ β₂,\\ ...,\\ βₘ} are the coefficients representing the\n  impact of each independent variable on y.\n\\item\n  \\texttt{x₁,\\ x₂,\\ ...,\\ xₘ} are the independent variables.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Example:} Predicting a house’s price based on its size (square\nfootage) and number of bedrooms.\n\n\\textbf{Step-by-Step Process:}\n\n\\begin{enumerate}\n\\def\\labelenumi{\\arabic{enumi}.}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Gather Data:} Collect data on house prices, size, and number\n  of bedrooms.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Calculate Regression Coefficients:} Use the least squares\n  method to calculate the coefficients (β₀, β₁, β₂).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Evaluate the Model:} Assess the model’s accuracy using metrics\n  such as R-squared (a measure of how well the model fits the data).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Make Predictions:} Use the equation to predict the price of a\n  new house based on its size and number of bedrooms.\n\\end{enumerate}\n\n\\textbf{Best Practices:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Check for Linearity:} Ensure the relationship between the\n  variables is approximately linear. Transformations (e.g., logarithms)\n  can be applied if necessary.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Consider Multicollinearity:} Avoid including highly correlated\n  independent variables, as this can destabilize the regression\n  coefficients.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Interpret Coefficients Carefully:} The coefficients represent\n  the change in the dependent variable for a one-unit change in the\n  corresponding independent variable, holding all other variables\n  constant.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Common Pitfalls:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Non-Linear Relationships:} If the relationship is non-linear,\n  linear regression will not be effective. Consider using a non-linear\n  regression model or transforming the variables.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Outliers:} Outliers can disproportionately influence the\n  regression coefficients. Identify and handle outliers appropriately\n  (e.g., remove them or use robust regression techniques).\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{3. Working with\nPredictors}\\label{working-with-predictors}\n\nPredictors are the variables used to make predictions in a machine\nlearning model. They represent the factors that are believed to\ninfluence the outcome you’re trying to predict. Understanding the\nrelationships between predictors and the outcome is crucial for building\nan effective model.\n\n\\textbf{Types of Predictors:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Numerical Predictors:} Continuous variables like age, income,\n  or temperature.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Categorical Predictors:} Discrete variables like gender,\n  region, or product type.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Example:} Predicting customer churn (whether a customer will\ncancel a subscription) based on factors like age, usage frequency,\ncustomer service interactions, and subscription type.\n\n\\textbf{Best Practices:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Feature Scaling:} Scale numerical predictors to have a similar\n  range of values to prevent variables with larger scales from\n  dominating the model.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{One-Hot Encoding:} Convert categorical predictors into\n  numerical representations using one-hot encoding.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{4. K-means Clustering}\\label{k-means-clustering}\n\nK-means clustering is an unsupervised learning algorithm that groups\ndata points into \\emph{k} clusters based on their similarity. The\nalgorithm aims to minimize the within-cluster sum of squares, which\nrepresents the average distance between data points and their respective\ncluster centroids.\n\n\\textbf{Step-by-Step Process:}\n\n\\begin{enumerate}\n\\def\\labelenumi{\\arabic{enumi}.}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Choose \\emph{k}}: Select the number of clusters (\\emph{k}) you\n  want to create. There are methods to determine an optimal \\emph{k}\n  (e.g., the elbow method).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Initialize Centroids:} Randomly initialize \\emph{k} centroids\n  (the centers of the clusters).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Assign Data Points:} Assign each data point to the nearest\n  centroid.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Update Centroids:} Recalculate the centroid of each cluster\n  based on the mean of the data points assigned to it.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Repeat Steps 3 \\& 4} until the centroids no longer change\n  significantly or a maximum number of iterations is reached.\n\\end{enumerate}\n\n\\textbf{Best Practices:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Determine \\emph{k}}: Selecting the optimal \\emph{k} is\n  crucial. Consider using the elbow method or silhouette analysis.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Scaling:} Scale the data points before applying k-means to\n  ensure that all features contribute equally to the distance\n  calculation.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{5. Using Decision Trees}\\label{using-decision-trees}\n\nDecision trees are a supervised learning algorithm that recursively\npartitions data based on feature values to create a tree-like structure\nthat can be used to predict the outcome.\n\n\\textbf{Key Concepts:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Node:} Represents a test on a single feature.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Branch:} Represents the outcome of the test.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Leaf Node:} Represents the final prediction.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Step-by-Step Process:}\n\n\\begin{enumerate}\n\\def\\labelenumi{\\arabic{enumi}.}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Split Data:} The algorithm recursively splits the dataset\n  based on the feature that best separates the data into different\n  classes.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Create Nodes and Branches:} Each split creates a new node and\n  branches based on the resulting values.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Grow the Tree:} The tree grows until a stopping criterion is\n  met (e.g., maximum depth, minimum number of samples per leaf).\n\\end{enumerate}\n\n\\textbf{Best Practices:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Pruning:} Avoid overfitting by pruning the tree to remove\n  unnecessary branches.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Feature Selection:} Choose features that are most informative\n  and relevant to the prediction task.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{6. Logistic Regression}\\label{logistic-regression}\n\nLogistic regression is a popular classification algorithm that predicts\nthe probability of a binary outcome (0 or 1) based on one or more\nindependent variables.\n\n\\textbf{Key Concepts:}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Sigmoid Function:} The sigmoid function maps the linear\n  combination of variables to a probability between 0 and 1.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Log Odds:} The logarithm of the odds ratio, which is used to\n  calculate the coefficients of the model.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Step-by-Step Process:}\n\n\\begin{enumerate}\n\\def\\labelenumi{\\arabic{enumi}.}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Build the Model:} Train the logistic regression model using\n  the training data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Predict Outcomes:} Use the trained model to predict the\n  probability of a binary outcome for new data points.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Set a Threshold:} Set a threshold (e.g., 0.5) to classify the\n  outcome as 0 or 1 based on the predicted probability.\n\\end{enumerate}\n\n\\subsection{5. Summary \\& Actionable\nTakeaways}\\label{summary-actionable-takeaways}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Understand your data:} Proper data preparation and exploration\n  are fundamental to successful machine learning.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Choose the right algorithm:} Select the algorithm that best\n  suits the problem’s characteristics and data type.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Evaluate your model:} Use appropriate evaluation metrics to\n  assess the model’s performance and identify areas for improvement.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Iterate and refine:} Machine learning is an iterative process\n  – experiment with different models and parameters, and continually\n  refine your approach based on your results.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{6. Glossary of Terms}\\label{glossary-of-terms}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Machine Learning:} A field of computer science that enables\n  systems to learn from data without being explicitly programmed.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Supervised Learning:} A type of machine learning where the\n  algorithm learns from labeled data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Unsupervised Learning:} A type of machine learning where the\n  algorithm learns from unlabeled data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Regression:} A supervised learning task where the algorithm\n  learns to predict a continuous numerical value.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Classification:} A supervised learning task where the\n  algorithm learns to assign data points to predefined categories or\n  classes.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Linear Regression:} A statistical method for modeling the\n  relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent\n  variables.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Logistic Regression:} A statistical method for predicting the\n  probability of a binary outcome.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{K-means Clustering:} An unsupervised learning algorithm that\n  partitions data into \\emph{k} clusters.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Principal Component Analysis (PCA):} A dimensionality\n  reduction technique that transforms data into a new coordinate system.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Support Vector Machine (SVM):} A supervised learning algorithm\n  that finds an optimal hyperplane to separate data points.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Bias:} A systematic error in a model due to simplifying\n  assumptions.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Variance:} A measure of the sensitivity of a model to changes\n  in the training data.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Bias-Variance Tradeoff:} The challenge of balancing bias and\n  variance in a model.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Cross-Validation:} A technique for evaluating model\n  performance by splitting the data into multiple sets for training and\n  testing.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Centroid:} The center of a cluster in k-means clustering.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{7. Knowledge Assessment (Bloom’s Taxonomy\nBased)}\\label{knowledge-assessment-blooms-taxonomy-based}\n\n\\subsubsection{Part A: Recall \\& Comprehension (10\nMCQs)}\\label{part-a-recall-comprehension-10-mcqs}\n\n\\textbf{Q1:} Which of the following best describes unsupervised\nlearning?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Training a model with labeled data.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Discovering patterns in unlabeled data.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Predicting a continuous numerical value.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Classifying data into predefined categories.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q2:} What is the primary goal of linear regression?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To predict categorical outcomes.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To find the best-fitting line through data points.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To group data points into clusters.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To maximize the accuracy of a classification model.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q3:} What is a key characteristic of a high-variance model?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It has low bias and consistently accurate predictions.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It overfits the training data and generalizes poorly.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It has high bias and consistently underperforms.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It performs equally well on both training and test data.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q4:} Which of the following is a common application of k-means\nclustering?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Predicting house prices.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Customer segmentation.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Detecting spam emails.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Recommending products to customers.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q5:} What does the sigmoid function do in logistic regression?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It finds the optimal coefficients for the model.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It maps a linear combination of variables to a probability between 0\n    and 1.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It calculates the gradient of the loss function.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    It performs dimensionality reduction.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q6:} What is the purpose of Principal Component Analysis (PCA)?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To classify data into different categories.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To reduce the dimensionality of data while preserving important\n    information.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To build a decision tree model.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To perform linear regression.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q7:} What is a support vector in the context of Support Vector\nMachines (SVMs)?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A point on the decision boundary that maximizes the margin.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A data point used to train the model.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A parameter that controls the complexity of the model.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A measure of the error in the model’s predictions.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q8:} What is the main purpose of cross-validation?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To train a single model on all available data.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To estimate the model’s performance on unseen data.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To simplify the model’s architecture.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To reduce the amount of data needed for training.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q9:} What does the “bias-variance tradeoff” refer to in machine\nlearning?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The trade-off between accuracy and interpretability.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The balance between model complexity and the risk of overfitting.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The trade-off between data volume and computational resources.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The trade-off between training time and prediction speed.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q10:} In logistic regression, what does the logit function\nrepresent?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The probability of the outcome being 1.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The logarithm of the odds ratio.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The value of the dependent variable.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The slope of the regression line.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{Part B: Application \\& Analysis (5 Short Answer\nQuestions)}\\label{part-b-application-analysis-5-short-answer-questions}\n\n\\textbf{Q11:} Describe a scenario where you would choose k-means\nclustering over linear regression. Explain your reasoning.\n\n\\textbf{Q12:} You have a dataset with many features and you suspect\noverfitting is a problem. What steps would you take to address this\nissue?\n\n\\textbf{Q13:} Explain how a logistic regression model would be used to\npredict whether a customer will click on an online advertisement.\n\n\\textbf{Q14:} A dataset has a high degree of multicollinearity between\nits predictor variables. How would this affect the interpretation of the\nregression coefficients and what actions could you take to mitigate the\nissue?\n\n\\textbf{Q15:} Imagine you’re building a model to predict housing prices.\nDiscuss the importance of feature scaling and explain why it might be\nnecessary.\n\n\\subsubsection{Part C: Synthesis \\& Evaluation (2 Critical Thinking\nChallenges)}\\label{part-c-synthesis-evaluation-2-critical-thinking-challenges}\n\n\\textbf{Q16:} You are given a dataset with both numerical and\ncategorical features. Design a machine learning approach that could\neffectively utilize both types of data.\n\n\\textbf{Q17:} You have trained a Support Vector Machine (SVM) model on a\ntraining dataset. However, the model performs poorly on a separate test\ndataset. What are some possible reasons for this discrepancy and what\nsteps could you take to improve the model’s performance?\n\n\\begin{center}\\rule{0.5\\linewidth}{0.5pt}\\end{center}\n\n\\end{document}\n"
